<h3>What is blood bank?</h3>

<p>A blood bank is a facility that collects, separates, and stores blood for transfusion.
 Blood banks are vital to saving lives because donated blood can be used to treat people who are critically ill 
 or in need of a blood transfusion. </p>
 
<h3>What is in a blood bank? </h3>

<p>Red blood cells: Carry oxygen<p>
<p>Platelets: Help blood clot<p>
<p>Plasma: Contains proteins that regulate coagulation and healing</p>


<h3>How does blood banking work?</h3>

<p>Blood banks use medical technology to safely store, process, and screen blood 
Blood is separated into its components so it can be used most effectively for each patient </p>

<h3>Why is blood donation important? </h3>

<p>Donating blood can save lives</p>
<p>Donating blood can help improve your health</p>
<p>Donating blood can help you learn more about your body</p>
<p>Donating blood can help stabilize blood bank collections</p>
<p>Donating blood can help maintain diversity in the blood supply</p>

<h3>How can you help?</h3>
<p> Donate blood, Encourage others to donate blood, and Be aware of the importance of diversity in the blood supply. </p>

